d\mathbf {V}: this is just the same as d\mathbf {P}. In particular, \mathbf {O} = \mathbf {P} \mathbf {V} so that

     d\mathbf {V} = \frac {\partial  \phi (\mathbf {O})}{\partial  \mathbf {V}} = \frac {\partial  \phi (\mathbf {O})}{\partial  \mathbf {O}} \frac {\partial  \mathbf {O}}{\partial  \mathbf {V}} = \mathbf {P}^T d\mathbf {O} 


Furthermore, we can see this by writing \mathbf {O}_{ik} = \sum _{j} \mathbf {P}_{ij} \mathbf {V}_{jk}. Then

      \begin {align*}
       d\mathbf {V}_{jk} &= \sum _{i} \frac {\partial  \phi }{\partial  \mathbf {O}_{ik}} \cdot  \frac {\partial  \mathbf {O}_{ik}}{\partial  \mathbf {V}_{jk}}  \\
                        &= \sum _{i} d\mathbf {O}_{ik} \mathbf {P}_{ij} \\
                        &= \sum _{i} \frac {\exp  \left (\mathbf {Q}_{i} \cdot  \mathbf {K}_{j}\right )}{\mathbf {L}_{i}} d\mathbf {O}_{ik}
      .\end {align*}

