fr:mainmatter.html:div:
Claim. 
  The Jacobian of the softmax function for \mathbf {y} = \mathrm {softmax}(\mathbf {x}) is given by

    \begin {align*}
      \frac {\partial  y_i}{\partial  x_j} = y_i(\delta _{ij} - y_j),
    \end {align*}

  or, in matrix form,

    \begin {align*}
      J = \mathrm {diag}(\mathbf {y}) - \mathbf {y}\mathbf {y}^\top .
    \end {align*}

html:div.style:
margin: 1em 0 1em 0.25em;
padding: 0.5em 1.1em 0.5em 1.2em;
border-left: 4px solid rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.4);
border-radius: var(--radius);
background-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.03);

fr:mainmatter.html:div:
Proof. 
    Write y_i = e^{x_i} / S with S = \sum _{k=1}^{d} e^{x_k}, so that \partial  S / \partial  x_j = e^{x_j}. By the quotient rule,

    \begin {align*}
      \frac {\partial  y_i}{\partial  x_j}
        &= \frac {\delta _{ij} e^{x_i} S - e^{x_i} e^{x_j}}{S^2} \\
        &= \delta _{ij}\frac {e^{x_i}}{S} - \frac {e^{x_i}}{S}\frac {e^{x_j}}{S} \\
        &= \delta _{ij} y_i - y_i y_j \\
        &= y_i(\delta _{ij} - y_j).
    \end {align*}

    Collecting these entries into a matrix, the diagonal contributes y_i along \mathrm {diag}(\mathbf {y}) and the -y_i y_j term is the outer product \mathbf {y}\mathbf {y}^\top , giving J = \mathrm {diag}(\mathbf {y}) - \mathbf {y}\mathbf {y}^\top .
